node.text:
Biologists have discovered that Bruce – a disabled New Zealand kea (Nestor notabilis) – has been using tiny little pebbles to preen himself. Because there's nothing better than a nice exfoliation to clean yourself after a long day!

This is both the first time scientists have recorded a kea using a tool for self-care and the first scientific observation of a parrot using a pebble in this way. 
​
​Read more about Bruce at the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert
​
​📷: Patrick Wood/University of Auckland

node.text:
A bike... but TINY.
​
​😄 What creative cell art made from silica producing diatoms! Not only do these photosynthesizing organisms produce around half of Earth's oxygen, they're also a huge part of the food chains in our planet's waterways - feeding animals from insects to whales. 🐟🦀🐋
​
​📷 James Lowry/via @olympuslifescience

🥺 Please enjoy this death by cute.
​
​The adorable baby spiderling is only 1 mm big! ​Swipe to see the pretty "starry" abdomen of the male Maratus constellatus when they're all grown. 😍🕷️ 
​
​They hail from Western Australia and you can read more about this species discover last year throu the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷  Jurgen Otto/@otto_jurgen

These stunning impact craters adorning the surface of Mars can reveal some of the alien planet's secrets.
​
​Layering around the rims hint at past volcanic activity 🌋  You can read more through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert
​

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on September 16, 2021.

node.text:
Tiny things can still be beautiful! 😍 
​
​This false color stacked image shows a southern live oak leaf under 60x magnification.  The white star shapes are trichomes - or little plant hairs and the pink shows the stomata. 
​
​This image, taken by microscopist Jason Kirk  came first in the 2021 Nikon Small World Photomicrography Competition. How gorgeous! 
​
​📷: Jason Kirk

node.text:
This cute little flying contraption is a potential taxi of the future. 
​
​NASA's testing the prototype electric vertical takeoff and landing (eVTOL) helicopter. ​It's designed to carry passengers through the sky as an air taxi.
​
The first photo shows it in flight and the second shows it ready for take off at the Electric Flight Base near Big Sur, California.
​
​📷: Joby Aviation
​

node.text:
Behold the adorable face of a club-horned sawfly baby! 😍
​
Trichiosoma triangulum larva feast on leaves from common trees across North America like ash, willows, cherries and poplars. As adults these wasp relatives, with dark bodies and orange wings, look like flies. The females have a saw-like ovipositor for cutting into plant flesh to lay their eggs in.
​
​📷 masonmaron/@inaturalistorg

node.text:
This pair of colliding spiral galaxies, 105 million light-years away, was discovered all the way back in 1784. 😱 
​
​Despite its distance, NGC 520 is one of the brightest stars in the sky. The pair show the merging process in action - the parent galaxies disks have merged, but the nuclei have not yet coalesced. We imagine the star that astronomer William Herschel noted on 13 December 1784 wouldn't have looked quite as pretty as this Hubble photo though, which was taken in 2004.  
​
​📷: NASA, ESA, the Hubble Heritage (STScI/AURA)-ESA/Hubble Collaboration, and B. Whitmore (STScI)

node.text:
😮 These hilariously rude looking nightmares are somehow plant flowers?! 😂 
​
​They belong to a parasitic plant, called Jackal food (Hydnora africana), whose flowers emerge from under the southern African ground only after rain. Their fleshy disguise comes complete with a rotting stench with which they attract the insects that pollinate it. 🐝🌸 
​
Without leaves, they don't photosynthesize, instead stealing nutrients from other plants through their roots. They also grow potato-like fruits underground which are eaten by Jackals, porcupines and other animals.
​
​📷 Ebony Black, Public Domain Mark 1.0/Flickr/via @amnh

600 of these Nazi uranium cubes went missing in the US after World War II. Marie Curie's granddaughter used one as a door stop and scientists are on a mission to hunt down the rest. You can read more about this curious mystery through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷 John T. Consoli/University of Maryland

node.text:
Sometimes you've got to look back at where you've come from. 
​
​The first photo is a shot of Jupiter's moon Ganymede taken by the Hubble Space Telescope in 1996. Sure, it's a little blurry, but considering it's over 600 million kilometers away from us, the view isn't too bad. 
​
​But the second photo shows Ganymede in all that close-up cratered glory! This photo was taken by NASA's Jupiter-faring spacecraft, Juno in 2021. 
​
​What a difference 25 years can make! 
​
​1️⃣📷: NASA, ESA, John Spencer (SwRI Boulder)
​2️⃣📷: NASA/JPL-Caltech/SwRI/MSSS/Kevin M. Gill
